==Residents==
Carson City has served as one of the state’s centers for politics and business.  Every state governor since [[Denver S. Dickerson]] has resided in the [[Nevada Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]] located in Carson City.&lt;ref name=&quot;Early-Carson-p60&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last=Ballew|first=Susan J.|coauthors=Dolan, L. Trent|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uRuaIrzRP2cC&amp;pg=PA60&amp;dq=dickerson|title=Early Carson City|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]|page=60|year=2010|accessdate=November 20, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''See also: [[List of Governors of Nevada]].'' The following personalities took up a residence in Carson City at some point in their lives.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.visitcarsoncity.com/history/personalities.php Historic Personalities]&lt;/ref&gt;
*[[Abraham Curry]], founding father of Carson City and early politician
*[http://carsonpedia.com/Major_William_Ormsby William Ormsby], soldier and namesake of [[Ormsby County]] and [[Ormsby House]]
*[[Orion Clemens]], Secretary of Nevada Territory
*[[Mark Twain]], author (lived with his brother Orion)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.visitcarsoncity.com/history/people/mark_twain.php Mark Twain (Samuel Clemens) - Carson City]&lt;/ref&gt;
*[[Hank Monk]], stagecoach driver
*[[Duane Leroy Bliss|Duane L. Bliss]], timber businessman
*[[Dat-So-La-Lee]], Native American basket weaver and artist
*[[John Wayne]], actor (resided at the Ormsby House while filming the Shootist)
*[[George Washington Gale Ferris, Jr.|George Ferris]], creator of the [[Ferris Wheel]]
*[[Sarah Winnemucca]], Native American author
*[[Paul Laxalt]], former Nevada Governor and US Senator

==Transportation==
[[Image:US395SouthofCarsonCity.jpg|thumb|left|Looking south on [[U.S. Route 395 in Nevada|US 395]], just south of [[U.S. Route 50 in Nevada|US 50]] near Carson City]]
There are two highways in the city [[US Route 395]] and [[US Route 50 in Nevada|US Route 50]].&lt;ref name=rgjtemp&gt;{{cite news
|work=Reno Gazette Journal
|title = New Stretch of Freeway Opens in Carson
|url = http://www.rgj.com/article/20090925/NEWS/909250406/1321/NEWS
|date = September 25, 2009
|accessdate = May 29, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; Carson City is home to one under-construction freeway [[Interstate 580]].  Phase 1 of the Carson City Freeway Project from US 395, just north of the city, to US 50 was completed in February 2006 and Phase 2A, extending from Rt. 50 to Fairview Drive, was officially opened on September 24, 2009. Phase 2B, Fairview Drive to Rt. 50, awaits funding.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ccfreeway.com|title=Carson City Freeway|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Carson City Freeway}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Carson City's first modern bus system, Jump Around Carson, or JAC, opened to the public. JAC uses a smaller urban bus that is ideal for Carson City.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.carson-city.nv.us/Index.aspx?page=1436|title=Jump Around Carson|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Jump Around Carson}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, there is virtually no ground public transportation to other destinations.  Passenger trains haven't served Carson City since 1948, [[Greyhound Lines]] stopped their bus services to the town in 2006 and [[Amtrak]] discontinued their connecting thruway bus to [[Sacramento]] in 2008.  There is now only a limited Monday – Friday RTC bus service to [[Reno]] which is still served by both [[Greyhound]] and [[Amtrak]].

Carson City is also served by the [[Carson Airport]], which is a regional airport in the northern part of the city. [[Reno-Tahoe International Airport]], which is {{convert|28|mi|km}} away, handles international and domestic commercial flights.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.carsoncity-airport.com/Home.shtml|title=Carson City Airport|last=Staff Writer|publisher=Carson City Airport|accessdate=6-3-2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

