  <page>
    <title>Coal tar</title>
    <id>7466</id>
    <revision>
      <id>429167117</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-15T01:29:13Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <ip>78.86.61.94</ip>
      </contributor>
      <comment>/* Medical */</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Coal tar''' is a brown or black liquid of high [[viscosity]], which smells of [[naphthalene]] and [[aromatic hydrocarbon]]s. Coal tar is among the by-products when [[coal]] is 
[[carbonization|carbonized]] to make [[coke (fuel)|coke]] or [[coal gasification|gasified]] to make [[coal gas]]. Coal tars are complex and variable mixtures of [[phenols]], [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s (PAHs), and [[heterocyclic compound]]s, about 200 substances in all.&lt;ref name=&quot;c&quot;&gt;[http://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/toxprofiles/tp85-c2.pdf Toxicological profile for wood creosote, coal tar creosote, coal tar, coal tar pitch, and coal tar pitch volatiles] U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, page 19, September 2002&lt;/ref&gt;

==Applications==
===Pavement Sealcoat===

{{Main|Sealcoat}}

Coal tar is incorporated into some parking-lot [[sealcoat]] products, which are marketed as a means of protecting and beautifying underlying pavement.&lt;ref&gt;truthaboutcoaltar.com, [http://www.truthaboutcoaltar.com/aboutpavement.html ''About pavement sealer''], accessed April 3, 2011&lt;/ref&gt; Sealcoat products that are coal-tar based typically contain 20 to 35 percent coal-tar pitch.&lt;ref name=&quot;fs20113010&quot;&gt;Mahler, B.J., and Van Metre, P.C. [http://pubs.usgs.gov/fs/2011/3010/ ''Coal-Tar-Based Pavement Sealcoat, Polycyclic Aromatic Hydrocarbons (PAHs), and Environmental Health''], 2011&lt;/ref&gt; Substantial concerns have been raised about the safety of this application of coal tar, given that coal tar is known to cause cancer in humans &lt;ref&gt;International Agency for Research on Cancer [http://ntp.niehs.nih.gov/ntp/roc/eleventh/profiles/s048coal.pdf ''Coal tars and coal tar pitches''], 1980, accessed September 14, 2010&lt;/ref&gt; and that several PAH compounds in coal tar are toxic to aquatic life. Defenders of coal-tar use in sealcoat have pointed out that humans are exposed to PAHs through many pathways, and similarly that the urban environment has many potential sources of PAHs.&lt;ref&gt;truthaboutcoaltar.com, [http://www.truthaboutcoaltar.com/aboutcoaltar.html ''About Coal Tar and Polycyclic Aromatic Hydrocarbons (PAHs)''], accessed April 3, 2011&lt;/ref&gt;

The use of coal tar in sealcoats—at least in the United States—is regional,&lt;ref name=&quot;fs20113010&quot; /&gt; and several areas have banned its use in sealcoat products
&lt;ref&gt;City of Austin Watershed Protection Department. [http://www.ci.austin.tx.us/watershed/coaltar_main.htm  ''Coal Tar Sealant Ban''] accessed April 3, 2011&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;ref&gt;District Department of the Environment, [http://newsroom.dc.gov/show.aspx/agency/ddoe/section/2/release/17479 ''District Bans Coal-Tar Pavement Products''], 2009, accessed April 3, 2011&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;ref&gt;Dane County Office of Lakes and Watersheds, [http://www.danewaters.com/business/coalTar.aspx ''Ordinance on Coal Tar Sealants''] accessed April 3, 2011&lt;/ref&gt;

===Industrial===
Being flammable, coal tar is sometimes used for heating or to fire [[boiler]]s. Like most heavy oils, it must be heated before it will flow easily.

Tar was a vital component of the first sealed, or &quot;[[tarmac]]&quot;, roads. Coal tar was formerly used as one of the primary ingredients of [[Tarmac]]adam pavements, when mixed with ironworks [[slag]].&lt;ref&gt;John Sheail, ‘Hooley, Edgar Purnell (1860–1942)’, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, online edn, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/49486, accessed 21 June 2010]&lt;/ref&gt; Today, petroleum derived binders and sealers are more commonly used. These sealers are used to extend the life and lower maintenance cost associated with [[asphalt]] pavements, primarily in asphalt road paving, car parks and walkways.

A large part of the binders used in the graphite industry for making &quot;Green Blocks&quot; are Coke Oven Volatiles or COV. A considerable portion of these COV used as binders is Coal Tar. During the heating / Baking process of the green blocks as a part of commercial graphite production, most part of the coal tar binders gets vaporised and is generally burned in Incinerator to prevent release in the atmosphere as the COV and Coal Tar can be injurious to health.

Coal tar is also used to manufacture paints,synthetic dyes and photographic materials.

===Medical===
Also known as liquor carbonis detergens (LCD),&lt;ref&gt;Paghdal &amp; Schwartz, Topical tar: Back to the future, Dermatology and Pathology, August 2009&lt;/ref&gt; like [[pine tar]], it can be used in medicated [[shampoo]], [[Wrights Coal Tar Soap|soap]] and [[ointment]], as a treatment for [[dandruff]] and [[psoriasis]], as well as being used to kill and repel [[head lice]]. When used as a medication in the [[United States|U.S.]], coal tar preparations are considered an OTC ([[over-the-counter drug]]) pharmaceutical and are subject to regulation by the [[United States Food and Drug Administration]]. Name brands include [[Denorex]], Balnetar, Psoriasin, Tegrin, [[T/Gel]], and Neutar. When used in the extemporaneous preparation of topical medications, it is supplied in the form of Coal Tar Topical Solution [[United States Pharmacopeia|USP]], which consists of a [[percentage solution|20% w/v]] solution of coal tar in [[alcohol]], with an additional 5% w/v of [[polysorbate 80]];&lt;ref&gt;USP30-NF25 page 1817&lt;/ref&gt; this must then be diluted in an ointment base such as [[petrolatum]].

==Safety==
According to the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]], preparations that include more than 5 percent of crude coal tar are [[List of IARC Group 1 carcinogens|Group 1]] [[carcinogen]]. 

According to the [[National Psoriasis Foundation]] and the FDA, coal tar is a valuable, safe and inexpensive treatment option for millions of people with psoriasis and other scalp or skin conditions.&lt;ref&gt;[[National Psoriasis Foundation]], [http://www.psoriasis.org/news/stories/2001/20011202_coalcala.php The battle to save coal tar in California], December 3, 2001.&lt;/ref&gt; Coal tar concentrations between 0.5% and 5% are safe and effective for psoriasis, and no scientific evidence suggests that the coal tar in the concentrations seen in non-prescription treatments is carcinogenic. The NPF states that coal tar contains approximately 10,000 chemicals, of which only about 50% have been identified,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.psoriasis.org/treatment/psoriasis/topicals/tar.php National Psoriasis Foundation: Tar&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; and the composition of coal tar varies with its origin and type of coal (for example,: [[lignite]], [[bituminous coal|bituminous]] or [[anthracite]]) used to make it.

Coal tar causes [[sun poisoning|increased sensitivity to sunlight]],&lt;ref name=&quot;medicinenet&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title= Sun-Sensitive Drugs (Photosensitivity to Drugs) |url= http://www.medicinenet.com/sun-sensitive_drugs_photosensitivity_to_drugs/page5.htm |date= 2008-08-22 |page= 5 |work= MedicineNet |publisher= [[WebMD]] |accessdate=2010-09-22 }}&lt;/ref&gt; so skin treated with topical coal tar preparations should be protected from sunlight.

The residue from the [[distillation]] of high-temperature coal tar, primarily a complex mixture of three or more membered condensed ring [[aromatic hydrocarbon]]s, was listed on 28 October 2008 as a [[substance of very high concern]] by the [[European Chemicals Agency]].

