'''Chelsea Football Club''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|ˈ|tʃ|ɛ|l|s|iː}}) are an English [[Association football|football]] club based in [[West (London sub region)|West London]]. Founded in 1905, they play in the [[English Premier League|Premier League]] and have spent most of their history in the top tier of English football. Chelsea have been [[List of English football champions|English champions]] four times, [[FA Cup]] winners six times and [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] winners four times. They have also been successful in Europe, winning the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] twice.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/TrophyCabinet | title=Trophy Cabinet | work=chelseafc.com| accessdate=25 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The club had their first major success in [[1954-55 in English football|1955]], when they won the league championship. Chelsea won several cup competitions during the 1960s and 1970s, but after that did not win another major title until 1997. The past decade has been the most successful period in Chelsea’s history, capped by winning Premier League titles in [[2004–05 FA Premier League|2005]], [[2005–06 FA Premier League|2006]] and [[2009–10 Premier League|2010]], the latter as part of their first league and FA Cup &quot;[[Double (association football)|Double]]&quot;.

Despite their name, the club are not based in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], but in neighbouring [[London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham|Fulham]]. The club's home is the 41,841 capacity [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] football stadium in [[Fulham]],&lt;ref name=&quot;capacity&quot;/&gt; where they have played since their establishment. Since 2003 they have been owned by Russian billionaire [[Roman Abramovich]].&lt;ref name=&quot;takeover&quot;&gt;{{cite news | date=2 July 2003 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3036838.stm | title=Russian businessman buys Chelsea | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=11 February 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Chelsea's regular [[Kit (association football)|kit]] colours are royal blue shirts and shorts with white socks, the combination used since the 1960s. The club crest has been changed several times in attempts to modernise or re-brand; the current crest, featuring a ceremonial lion holding a staff, is a modified version of one first adopted in the 1950s.&lt;ref name=&quot;new crest&quot;&gt;{{cite news | date=12 November 2004 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4008257.stm | title=Chelsea centenary crest unveiled | publisher=BBC Sport| accessdate=2 January 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; The club has sustained the fifth highest average all-time attendance in English football.&lt;ref name=&quot;attendance&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.nufc.com/2010-11html/attendance-all-time.html | title=All Time League Attendance Records | accessdate=13 September 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Their average home gate for the [[2010–11 in English football|2010–11 season]] was 41,435, the sixth highest in the Premier League.&lt;ref name=&quot;tonykempster.co.uk&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.tonykempster.co.uk/prematt.htm?comp=1 | title=Attendances 2009/10 | author=Kempster, Tony | accessdate=22 May 2010 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
{{Details|History of Chelsea F.C.}}
{{For|information on the current season|Chelsea F.C. season 2010–11}}
[[File:Chelsea Team 1905.jpg|thumb|250 px|The [[History of Chelsea F.C.|first Chelsea team]] in September 1905]]
Chelsea were founded on 10 March 1905 at The Rising Sun pub (now The Butcher's Hook),&lt;ref name=&quot;teamhistory&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/TeamHistory/0,,10268~1800325,00.html|title=Team History|publisher=Chelsea FC|accessdate=11 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; opposite the present-day main entrance to the ground on [[Fulham Road]], and were elected to the Football League shortly afterwards. The club's early years saw little success; the closest they came to winning a major trophy was reaching the [[1915 FA Cup Final]], where they lost to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Chelsea gained a reputation for signing big-name players&lt;ref name=&quot;glanville&quot;&gt;{{cite news | date=10 January 2004 | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article992039.ece | title=Little sign of change for Chelsea and their impossible dreams | work=Times Online| accessdate=15 March 2009 | author=[[Brian Glanville]] }}&lt;/ref&gt; and for being entertainers, but made little impact on the English game in the inter-war years.

Former [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and England centre-forward [[Ted Drake]] became manager in 1952 and proceeded to modernise the club. He removed the club's [[Chelsea pensioner]] crest, improved the youth set-up and training regime, rebuilt the side, and led Chelsea to their first major trophy success — the League championship — in 1954–55. The following season saw UEFA create the [[UEFA Champions League|European Champions' Cup]], but after objections from [[The Football League]] and the [[The Football Association|FA]] Chelsea were persuaded to withdraw from the competition before it started.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | date=27 April 2005 | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,762-1586242,00.html | title=The great Chelsea surrender | work=Times Online | accessdate=29 December 2006 |author=[[Brian Glanville]] }}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Chelsea FC League Performance 1906-2008.PNG|thumb|left|Chart showing the progress of Chelsea's league finishes from 1905–1906 to [[Premier League 2007-08|2007–08]]]]

They challenged for honours throughout the 1960s, and endured several near-misses. They were on course for a treble of League, FA Cup and League Cup going into the final stages of the 1964–65 season, winning the League Cup but faltering late on in the other two.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill, Rick | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography – The Definitive Story of the First 100 Years| publisher=Headline Book Publishing Ltd| year=2006| isbn=978-075531466-9 | page=196}}&lt;/ref&gt; In three seasons the side were beaten in three major semi-finals and were FA Cup runners-up. Chelsea won the [[1970 FA Cup Final|FA Cup in 1970]], beating [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] 2–1 in a final replay. Chelsea took their first European honour, a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] triumph, the following year, with another replayed win, this time over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in [[Athens]].

The late 1970s through to the 1980s was a turbulent period for Chelsea. An ambitious redevelopment of Stamford Bridge threatened the financial stability of the club,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=84–87}}&lt;/ref&gt; star players were sold and the team were relegated. Further problems were caused by a notorious [[hooliganism|hooligan]] element among the support, which was to plague the club throughout the decade.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=143–157}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1982 Chelsea were, at the nadir of their fortunes, acquired by [[Ken Bates]] for the nominal sum of £1, although by now the Stamford Bridge freehold had been sold to property developers, meaning the club faced losing their home.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=89–90}}&lt;/ref&gt; On the pitch, the team had fared little better, coming close to relegation to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] for the first time, but in 1983 manager [[John Neal (footballer)|John Neal]] put together an impressive new team for minimal outlay. Chelsea won the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title in 1983–84 and established themselves in the top division, before being relegated again in 1988. The club bounced back immediately by winning the Second Division championship in 1988–89.
[[File:ChelseaFC flag.jpg|thumb|Chelsea supporters passing a [[tifo]] flag before a match]]
After a long-running legal battle, Bates reunited the stadium freehold with the club in 1992 by doing a deal with the banks of the property developers, who had been bankrupted by a market crash.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=90–91}}&lt;/ref&gt; Chelsea's form in the new Premier League was unconvincing, although they did reach the [[1994 FA Cup Final]]. It was not until the appointment of former [[Ballon d'Or|European Footballer of the Year]] [[Ruud Gullit]] as player-manager in 1996 that their fortunes changed. He added several top-class international players to the side, as the club [[1997 FA Cup Final|won the FA Cup in 1997]] and established themselves as one of England's top sides again. Gullit was replaced by [[Gianluca Vialli]], who led the team to victory in the [[1998 Football League Cup Final|League Cup Final]] and the [[1998 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final|Cup Winners' Cup Final]] in 1998, the [[2000 FA Cup Final|FA Cup in 2000]] and the UEFA Champions League quarter-finals in 2000. Vialli was sacked in favour of another Italian, [[Claudio Ranieri]], who guided Chelsea to the [[2002 FA Cup Final]] and Champions League qualification in 2002–03.

In June 2003, Bates sold Chelsea to Russian billionaire Roman Abramovich for £140 million, completing what was then the biggest-ever sale of an English football club.&lt;ref name=&quot;takeover&quot;/&gt; Over £100 million was spent on new players, but Ranieri was unable to deliver any trophies, so he was replaced by Portuguese coach [[José Mourinho]]. Under Mourinho, Chelsea became the fifth English team to win back-to-back league championships since the Second World War ([[FA Premier League 2004–05|2004–05]] and [[FA Premier League 2005–06|2005–06]]),&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | url=http://www.sportinglife.com/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/06/03/12/SOCCER_Chelsea.html&amp;TEAMHD=soccer | title=Terry Eyes Back-to-Back Titles | publisher=Sporting Life | accessdate=22 January 2007 | author=Matt Barlow|date=12 March 2006 }}&lt;/ref&gt; in addition to winning an FA Cup ([[2007 FA Cup Final|2007]]) and two League Cups ([[2005 Football League Cup Final|2005]] and [[2007 Football League Cup Final|2007]]). In September 2007 Mourinho was replaced by [[Avram Grant]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | date=20 September 2007 | title=Chelsea name Grant as new manager | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/7004083.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=21 September 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; who led the club to their [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|first UEFA Champions League final]], which they lost on [[Penalty Shootout (football)|penalties]] to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. Grant was fired days later&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=24 May 2008 |
title=Grant sacked as Chelsea manager |
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/7418774.stm |
publisher=BBC Sport |
accessdate=24 August 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; and succeeded by [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]] in July 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/Homepage/article_1326948 |title=Scolari is new Chlesea manager |publisher=Chelsea FC |accessdate=11 June 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Scolari spent only seven months in the job before being dismissed after a string of poor results.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=9 February 2009 |
title=Chelsea sack Scolari |
url=http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1021097.html?cid=rssfeed&amp;att= |
work=FIFA.com |
accessdate=24 August 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Russia national football team|Russia]] coach [[Guus Hiddink]] was appointed caretaker manager until the end of the 2008–09 season,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/7882667.stm|title=Chelsea confirm Hiddink as coach|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 February 2009 | date=11 February 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; and guided Chelsea to a second [[2009 FA Cup Final|FA Cup triumph]] in three years.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/8060989.stm|title=Chelsea 2–1 Everton |publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 June 2009|date=30 May 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;
Two days later, former [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] coach [[Carlo Ancelotti]] was confirmed as Chelsea's new manager.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|date=6 January 2009|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/jun/01/carlo-ancelotti-chelsea-three-years|title=Carlo Ancelotti signs three-year deal with Chelsea|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; In his first season, Ancelotti led Chelsea to their first [[2009–10 Premier League|league]] and [[2010 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]] &quot;[[The Double|Double]]&quot;; in addition, Chelsea became the first English top-flight side to score over 100 league goals in a season since [[1962–63 in English football|1963]].&lt;ref name=Wigan80&gt;{{cite news |
date=9 May 2010 |
title=Chelsea 8–0 Wigan|
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8663686.stm |
publisher=BBC Sport|
accessdate=16 May 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;
Ancelotti parted company with Chelsea on 22 May 2011 after a trophyless season that saw the Blues lose in the quarter finals of Champions League, and finish runners-up in the Premier League, to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. &lt;ref&gt;http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~2364758,00.html&lt;/ref&gt;

==Stamford Bridge==
{{details|Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge}}
[[File:Chelsea-ilkmac.jpg|right|frame|Chelsea ''vs.'' [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at Stamford Bridge on 23 September 1905; Chelsea won 1–0.]]

Chelsea have only ever had one home ground, Stamford Bridge, where they have played since foundation. It was officially opened on 28 April 1877. For the first 28 years of its existence it was used almost exclusively by the London Athletics Club as an arena for athletics meetings and not at all for football. In 1904 the ground was acquired by businessman [[Gus Mears]] and his brother [[Joseph Mears|Joseph]], who had previously acquired additional land (formerly a large market garden) with the aim of staging football matches on the now 12.5 acre (51,000 m²) site.&lt;ref name = &quot;stadium&quot;/&gt;

Stamford Bridge was designed for the Mears family by the noted football architect [[Archibald Leitch]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=69–71}}&lt;/ref&gt; They offered to lease the stadium to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], but were turned down. As a consequence, the owners decided to form their own football club to occupy their new ground. Most football clubs were founded first, and then sought grounds in which to play, but Chelsea were founded for Stamford Bridge. Since there was already a football club named Fulham in the borough, the founders decided to adopt the name of the adjacent borough of Chelsea for the new club, having also considered names such as ''Kensington FC'', ''Stamford Bridge FC'' and ''London FC''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=55}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Starting with an open bowl-like design and one covered terrace, Stamford Bridge had an original capacity of around 100,000.&lt;ref name = &quot;stadium&quot;/&gt; The early 1930s saw the construction of a terrace on the southern part of the ground with a roof that covered around one fifth of the stand. It eventually became known as the &quot;Shed End&quot;, the home of Chelsea's most loyal and vocal supporters, particularly during the 1960s, 70s and 80s. The exact origins of the name are unclear, but the fact that the roof looked like a corrugated iron shed roof played a part.&lt;ref name=&quot;stadium&quot;&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/StadiumHistoryHistory |
 title=Stadium History |
 work=chelseafc.com|
 accessdate=21 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:West Stand Champions.jpg|thumb|265px|left|View from the West Stand, Stamford Bridge during a Champions League game]]
During the late 1960s and early 70s, the club's owners embarked on a modernisation of Stamford Bridge with plans for a 50,000 all-seater stadium.&lt;ref name=&quot;stadium&quot;/&gt;
Work began on the East Stand in the early 1970s but the project was beset with problems and the cost almost brought the club to its knees, culminating in the [[Fee simple|freehold]] being sold to property developers. Following a long legal battle, it was not until the mid-1990s that Chelsea's future at the stadium was secured and renovation work resumed.&lt;ref name=&quot;stadium&quot;/&gt; The north, west and southern parts of the ground were converted into all-seater stands and moved closer to the pitch, a process completed by 2001.

When Stamford Bridge was redeveloped in the [[Ken Bates]] era many additional features were added to the complex including two hotels, apartments, bars, restaurants, the Chelsea Megastore, and an interactive visitor attraction called Chelsea World of Sport. The intention was that these facilities would provide extra revenue to support the football side of the business, but they were less successful than hoped and before the Abramovich takeover in 2003 the debt taken on to finance them was a major burden on the club. Soon after the takeover a decision was taken to drop the &quot;Chelsea Village&quot; brand and refocus on Chelsea as a football club. However, the stadium is sometimes still referred to as part of ''&quot;Chelsea Village&quot;'' or ''&quot;The Village&quot;''.

[[File:Stamford-Bridge,WestStand entrance, day.jpg|thumb|255px|The Stamford Bridge West Stand – Entrance.]]
The Stamford Bridge [[Freehold (law)|freehold]], the [[Association football pitch|pitch]], the turnstiles and Chelsea's [[naming rights]] are now owned by [[Chelsea Pitch Owners]], a non-profit organisation in which fans are the shareholders. The CPO was created to ensure the stadium could never again be sold to developers. As a condition for using the Chelsea FC name, the club has to play its first team matches at Stamford Bridge, which means that if the club moves to a new stadium, they may have to change their name.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=91–92}}&lt;/ref&gt;
Chelsea's [[Cobham Training Centre|training ground]] is located in [[Cobham, Surrey]]. Chelsea moved to Cobham in 2004. Their previous training ground in [[Harlington, London|Harlington]] was taken over by [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] in 2005.&lt;ref&gt;Veysey, Wayne (24 May 2005), [http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/article-18829718-qpr-take-over-chelsea-training-ground.do QPR take over Chelsea training ground], ''Evening Standard''&lt;/ref&gt; The new training facilities in Cobham were completed in 2007.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2007/07/05/chelsea_ground_feature.shtml Chelsea's New Training Ground For The Future] BBC London, 5 July 2007&lt;/ref&gt;

The club plans to increase the capacity of Stamford Bridge to over 50,000. Owing to its location in a built-up part of London on a main road and next to two railway lines, fans can only enter the stadium through the [[Fulham Road]] entrances, which places severe constraints on expansion due to [[Occupational safety and health|health and safety]] regulations.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=76 }}&lt;/ref&gt; As a result, Chelsea have been linked with a move away from Stamford Bridge to sites including the [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre]], [[Battersea Power Station]] and the [[Chelsea Barracks]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | date = 20 January 2006
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4630618.stm
 | title = Chelsea plan Bridge redevelopment
 | publisher = BBC Sport
 | accessdate = 1 January 2007
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; However, the club have consistently affirmed their desire to keep Chelsea at their current home.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | date = 12 April 2006
 | url = http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/0412/stamfordbridge.html?rss
 | title = Kenyon confirms Blues will stay at Stamford Bridge
 | publisher = RTÉ Sport
 | accessdate = 1 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | date = 9 November 2008
 | url = http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~1448876,00.html
 | title = Observer Stadium Story Denied
 | publisher = Chelseafc.com
 | accessdate = 19 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
 | date = 10 November 2010
 | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1328071/Chelsea-deny-Earls-Court-ditch-Stamford-Bridge.html
 | title = Chelsea deny they're to ditch Stamford Bridge for 60,000 stadium at Earls Court
 | publisher = Daily Mail
 | accessdate = 19 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Stamford Bridge has been used for a variety of other sporting events since 1905. It hosted the [[FA Cup Final]] from 1920 to 1922,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/CupFinalResults |
 title=Cup Final Statistics |
 work=TheFA.com|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; has held ten [[FA Cup Semi-finals|FA Cup semi-finals]] (most recently in [[1977–78 FA Cup|1978]]), ten [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] matches (the last in [[1970 FA Charity Shield|1970]]), and three [[England national football team|England international]] matches, the last in 1932; it was also the venue for an unofficial ''Victory International'' in 1946.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslUnoff.html |
 title=England's Matches: Unofficial |
 work=Englandfootballonline|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; In October 1905 it hosted a [[rugby union]] match between the [[The Original All Blacks|All Blacks]] and Middlesex,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/allblacks.html |
 title=All Blacks |
 work=Rugbyfootballhistory.com|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; and in 1914 hosted a [[baseball]] match between the touring [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] and the [[Chicago White Sox]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.baseballgb.co.uk/?p=9582 |
 title=Countdown to SABR Day 2011 |
 work=BaseballGB.co.uk|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; It was the venue for a [[boxing]] match between world [[flyweight]] champion [[Jimmy Wilde]] and Joe Conn in 1918.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/casey/MC_Wilde.htm |
 title=Jimmy Wilde: The Original Explosive Thin Man |
 work=Cyberboxingzone.com|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; The running track was used for [[dirt track racing]] between 1928 and 1932,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.guskuhn.net/GKuhn/Stamford%20Bridge/StamfordBrdgIndex.htm |
 title=Stamford Bridge Speedway |
 work=guskuhn.net|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[greyhound racing]] from 1937 to 1968, and [[Midget car racing]] in 1948.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.speedcarworld.com.au/default.asp?Page=Release&amp;Id=8958| title=U. S. Invades England 1948|work=speedcarworld.com| accessdate=19 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1980, Stamford Bridge hosted the first international [[Floodlights (sport)|floodlit]] [[cricket]] match in the UK, between [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]] and the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.spincricket.com/tag/invention-of-twenty20/ |
 title=Twenty20 before Twenty20 |
 work=spincricket.com|
 accessdate=18 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; It was also the home stadium of the [[London Monarchs]] [[American Football]] team for the [[1997 London Monarchs season|1997 season]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.britballnow.co.uk/History/Britball%20Teams/LONDONMONARCHS.htm| title=London Monarchs|work=Britballnow.co.uk| accessdate=19 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Crest==
Since the club's foundation, Chelsea have had four main crests, though all underwent minor variations. In 1905, Chelsea adopted as their first crest the image of a [[Chelsea pensioner]], which obviously contributed to the &quot;pensioner&quot; nickname, and remained for the next half-century, though it never appeared on the shirts. As part of [[Ted Drake]]'s modernisation of the club from 1952 onwards, he insisted that the pensioner badge be removed from the match day programme in order to change the club's image and that a new crest be adopted.&lt;ref name=&quot;crests&quot;&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/ClubBadges |
 title=Club Badges |
 work=chelseafc.com|accessdate = 21 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; As a stop-gap, a temporary emblem comprising simply the initials C.F.C. was adopted for one year.

In 1953, Chelsea's crest was changed to an upright blue lion looking backwards and holding a [[staff (stick)|staff]], which was to endure for the next three decades. This crest was based on elements in the [[coat of arms]] of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Chelsea]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.civicheraldry.co.uk/lcc.html#chelsea%20bc |
 title=CHELSEA METROPOLITAN BOROUGH COUNCIL|
 work=Civic Heraldry of England and Wales|
 accessdate = 21 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; with the &quot;lion rampant regardant&quot; taken from the arms of then club president [[Earl Cadogan|Viscount Chelsea]] and the staff from the [[Westminster Abbey|Abbots of Westminster]], former Lords of the Manor of Chelsea. It also featured three red roses, to represent England, and two footballs. This was the first club badge to appear on shirts, since the policy of putting the crest on the shirts was only adopted in the early 1960s.&lt;ref name=&quot;crests&quot;/&gt;

In 1986, with [[Ken Bates]] now owner of the club, Chelsea's crest was changed again as part of another attempt to modernise and to capitalise on new marketing opportunities.&lt;ref name=&quot;crests&quot;/&gt; The new badge featured a more naturalistic non-heraldic lion, yellow and not blue, standing over the C.F.C. initials. It lasted for the next 19 years, with some modifications such as the use of different colours. With new ownership, and the club's centenary approaching, combined with demands from fans for the club's traditional badge to be restored, it was decided that the crest should be changed again in 2004. The new crest was officially adopted for the start of the 2005–06 season and marks a return to the older design of the blue heraldic lion holding a staff.&lt;ref name=&quot;new crest&quot;/&gt; As with previous crests, this one has appeared in various colours, including white and gold.

