 shorts = FFFFFM |
 socks = 191970 |
 title = Chelsea's first home colours, used from 1905 until c.1912.
}}

Chelsea have always worn blue shirts, although they initially adopted a lighter shade than the current version, and unlike today wore white shorts and dark blue socks. The lighter blue was taken from the racing colours of then club president, [[Earl Cadogan]]. The light blue shirts were short-lived, however, and replaced by a royal blue version in around 1912.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill, Rick | title=Chelsea Football Club: The Official History in Pictures| year=2006| isbn=0-7553-1467-0}} p. 212&lt;/ref&gt; In the 1960s Chelsea manager [[Tommy Docherty]] changed the kit again, switching to blue shorts (which have remained ever since) and white socks, believing it made the club's colours more modern and distinctive, since no other major side used that combination; this kit was first worn during the 1964–65 season.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Mears, Brian | title=Chelsea: Football Under the Blue Flag| publisher=Mainstream Sport| year=2002| isbn=1-84018-658-5 | page=42 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Since then Chelsea have always worn white socks with their home kit apart from a short spell from 1985 to 1992, when blue socks were reintroduced.

Chelsea's traditional away colours are all yellow or all white with blue trim, but, as with most teams, they have had some more unusual ones. The first away strip consisted of black and white stripes and for one game in the 1960s the team wore blue and black stripes, inspired by [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Inter Milan]]'s kit, again at Docherty's behest.&lt;ref&gt;The &quot;Inter Milan&quot; kit was worn for an FA Cup semi-final against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], on 23 April 1966. Reference: Mears (2002), p. 58&lt;/ref&gt; Other memorable away kits include a mint green strip in the 1980s, a red and white checked one in the early 90s and a graphite and tangerine edition in the mid-1990s.&lt;ref&gt;All kits are discussed on the club's official website {{cite web
 | url = http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/ClassicKits
 | title= Kits
 | work = chelseafc.com
 | accessdate = 1 January 2007
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Chelsea's kit is currently manufactured by [[Adidas]], which is contracted to supply the club's kit from 2006 to 2011. Previously, the kit was manufactured by [[Umbro]] (1968–81), [[Le Coq Sportif]] (1981–86), The Chelsea Collection (1986–87) and Umbro again (1987–2006). Chelsea's first shirt sponsor was [[Gulf Air]], agreed midway through the 1983–84 season. Following that, the club were sponsored by Grange Farms, [[Peter Foster|Bai Lin Tea]] and Italian company Simod before a long-term deal was signed with computer manufacturer [[Commodore International]] in 1989; [[Amiga]], an off-shoot of Commodore, also appeared on the shirts. Chelsea were subsequently sponsored by [[Coors Brewing Company|Coors]] beer (1995–97), Autoglass (1997–2001) and [[Emirates Airline]] (2001–05). Chelsea's current shirt sponsor is [[Samsung Group|Samsung]] &lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=2 May 2005 |
url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article387503.ece |
title=Clubs to cash in on mobile advertising |
work= Times Online |
accessdate=21 January 2010 |
author=Ashling O'Connor}}&lt;/ref&gt; who took over the sponsorship from their [[Samsung Mobile|mobile division]] in 2007–08.

==Supporters and rivalries==
[[File:Chelsea defend corner.jpg|thumb|Chelsea fans at a match against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], on 11 March 2006]]
Chelsea have the fifth highest average all-time attendance in [[Football in England|English football]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.nufc.com/2010-11html/attendance-all-time.html |
 title=All Time League Attendance Records |
 work= NUFC.com|
 accessdate=27 August 2006
 |date = 4 April 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; and regularly attract over 40,000 fans to Stamford Bridge; they were the fifth best-supported [[Premier League]] team in the 2009–10 season, with an average gate of 41,472.&lt;ref name=&quot;tonykempster.co.uk&quot;/&gt; Chelsea's traditional fanbase comes from all over the [[Greater London]] area including working-class parts such as [[Hammersmith]] and [[Battersea]], wealthier areas like Chelsea and [[Kensington]], and from the [[home counties]]. There are also numerous official supporters clubs in the United Kingdom and all over the world.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/SupporterClubsMap/0,,10268,00.html |
 title=Supporters Clubs Map |
 work= Chelseafc.com|
 accessdate=21 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

At matches Chelsea fans sing [[football chants|chants]] such as &quot;[[Carefree (chant)|Carefree]]&quot; (to the tune of [[Lord of the Dance]], whose lyrics were probably written by supporter Mick Greenaway&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=150}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://fanchants.com/football-songs/chelsea-chants/carefree/ &quot;Carefree&quot; audio sample]&lt;/ref&gt;), &quot;Ten Men Went to Mow&quot;, &quot;We All Follow the Chelsea&quot; (to the tune of [[Land of Hope and Glory]]), &quot;Zigga Zagga&quot;, and the celebratory &quot;Celery&quot;, with the latter often resulting in fans ritually throwing celery. The vegetable was banned inside Stamford Bridge after an incident involving [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] midfielder [[Cesc Fàbregas]] at the [[2007 Football League Cup Final|2007 League Cup Final]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=17 April 2002 |
url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,1563,685859,00.html |
title=Fans sent spinning after tossing salad |
work=The Guardian |
accessdate=1 January 2007 |
author=Scott Murray}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Chelsea do not have a traditional rivalry on the scale of the [[Merseyside derby]] or the [[North London derby]], and their [[West London derby]] with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] or [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] has not been as prominent over the years with due to the clubs often spending time in separate divisions. A 2004 survey by Planetfootball.com found that Chelsea fans consider their main rivalries to be with (in order): Arsenal, [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
url=http://www.thefootballnetwork.net/main/s120/st44186.htm |
 title=Football Rivalries: The Complete Results |
 work=Planetfootball.com |
 accessdate=2 January 2007
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Their rivalry with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] is said to have developed following the [[1967 FA Cup Final]], the first cup final held between two London clubs. Additionally, a [[Chelsea F.C. and Leeds United A.F.C. rivalry|strong rivalry]] with [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] dates back to several heated and controversial matches in the 1960s and 1970s, particularly the [[1970 FA Cup Final]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=321–325}}&lt;/ref&gt; More recently, a rivalry has grown with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] following repeated clashes in cup competitions.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
 url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/features/2011-05-19/peterborough-v-mk-dons-liverpool-v-chelsea-stoke-v-cardiff-six-best-modern-football-rivalries |
 title=Six very modern football rivalries |
 work=TalkSport |
 accessdate=23 May 2011
  | date=19 May 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

During the 1970s and 1980s in particular, Chelsea supporters were associated with [[Football (soccer) hooliganism|football hooliganism]]. The club's &quot;[[Football hooliganism|football firm]]&quot;, originally the Chelsea Shed Boys, now known as the [[Chelsea Headhunters]], were nationally notorious for violent acts against hooligans from other teams, such as [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]'s [[Inter City Firm]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]'s [[Millwall Bushwackers|Bushwackers]], both during and after matches.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
 url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/hooligans/1962503.stm |
 title=Making a new start |
 work=BBC News |
 accessdate=21 January 2007
  | date=2 May 2002}}&lt;/ref&gt; The increase in hooliganism in the 1980s led chairman Ken Bates to propose erecting an electric fence to deter them from invading the pitch; the proposal was rejected by the [[Greater London Council|GLC]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
 url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/3037508.stm |
 title=Bates: Chelsea's driving force |
 work=BBC Sport|
 accessdate = 21 January 2007 | date=2 July 2003}}&lt;/ref&gt; Since the 1990s there has been a marked decline in crowd trouble at matches, as a result of stricter policing, [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] in grounds and the advent of [[All-seater stadium|all-seater stadia]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=2 June 1998 |
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1998/hooligans/60146.stm |
title=Soccer hooliganism: Made in England, but big abroad |
publisher=BBC News|
accessdate=1 January 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; According to [[Home Office]] statistics 126 Chelsea fans were arrested for football-related offences during the [[2009-10 in English football|2009-10]] season, the third highest in the division, and 27 [[banning order]]s were issued, the fifth highest in the division.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/crime/football-arrests-banning-orders/fbo-2009-10?view=Binary |title=Statistics on football-related arrests and banning orders |accessdate=14 May 2011 |month=November |year=2010 |publisher=Home Office|format = PDF}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Records==
{{details|List of Chelsea F.C. records and statistics}}
[[File:Lampard playing.jpg|thumb|130px|Of Chelsea's current players, [[Frank Lampard]] has made the most appearances and scored the most goals]]
Chelsea's highest appearance-maker is ex-captain [[Ron Harris (footballer)|Ron Harris]], who played in 795 first-class games for the club between 1961 and 1980.&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot;&gt;For the appearance and goalscoring records of all Chelsea players, see {{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=399–410}}&lt;/ref&gt; This record is unlikely to be broken in the near future; Chelsea's current highest appearance-maker is Frank Lampard with 507.&lt;ref name=&quot;current player&quot;&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.soccerbase.com/ |
 title=soccerbase.com |accessdate = 13 December 2009 }}&lt;/ref&gt; The record for a Chelsea goalkeeper is held by Harris's contemporary, [[Peter Bonetti]], who made 729 appearances (1959–79). With 85 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] (83 while at the club), [[Frank Lampard]] of England is Chelsea's most capped international player.

[[Bobby Tambling]] is Chelsea's all-time top goalscorer, with 202 goals in 370 games (1959–70).&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot;/&gt; Eight other players have also scored over 100 goals for Chelsea: [[George Hilsdon]] (1906–12), [[George Mills (footballer)|George Mills]] (1929–39), [[Roy Bentley]] (1948–56), [[Jimmy Greaves]] (1957–61), [[Peter Osgood]] (1964–74 and 1978–79), [[Kerry Dixon]] (1983–92), Frank Lampard (2001–) and [[Didier Drogba]] (2004–). With 193 goals, Dixon is the only player to have come close to matching Tambling's record. Greaves holds the record for the most goals scored in one season (43 in 1960–61). Lampard is the top scorer currently at the club with 170.&lt;ref name=&quot;current player&quot;/&gt;

Officially, Chelsea's highest home attendance is 82,905 for a [[Football League First Division|First Division]] match against Arsenal on 12 October 1935. However, an estimated crowd of over 100,000 attended a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] against [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] team [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]] on 13 November 1945.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/TeamHistory |
 title= Team History |
 work=chelseafc.com |
accessdate = 21 January 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; The modernisation of Stamford Bridge during the 1990s and the introduction of all-seater stands mean that neither record will be broken for the foreseeable future. The current legal capacity of Stamford Bridge is 41,841.&lt;ref name=&quot;capacity&quot;/&gt;

Chelsea hold numerous records in [[Football in England|English]] and European football. They hold the record for the highest ever points total for a league season (95), the fewest goals conceded during a league season (15), the highest number of Premier League victories in a season (29), the highest number of clean sheets overall in a Premier League season (25) (all set during the [[FA Premier League 2004-05|2004–05 season]]),&lt;ref name=&quot;records&quot;&gt;{{cite news |
date=13 May 2005 |
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4545045.stm |
title=Mourinho proud of battling finish |
publisher=BBC Sport|
accessdate=29 August 2010
}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the most consecutive clean sheets from the start of a league season (6, set during the [[FA Premier League 2005-06|2005–06 season]]).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=17 September 2005 |
title=Charlton 0–2 Chelsea |
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4232354.stm |
publisher=BBC Sport|
accessdate=12 November 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

The club's 21–0 [[Aggregate score|aggregate]] victory over [[Jeunesse Hautcharage]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1971-72|UEFA Cup Winners' Cup in 1971]] remains a record in European competition.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/cwc.html#rec |
 title=Cup Winners' Cup Trivia |
 work=RSSSF |
accessdate = 21 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; Chelsea hold the record for the longest streak of unbeaten matches at home in the English top-flight, which lasted 86 matches from 20 March 2004 to 26 October 2008. They secured the record on 12 August 2007, beating the previous record of 63 matches unbeaten set by Liverpool between 1978 and 1980.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=12 August 2007 |
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6931067.stm |
title=Chelsea 3–2 Birmingham |
publisher=BBC Sport|
accessdate=9 October 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7674108.stm|title=Chelsea 0–1 Liverpool|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate = 26 October 2008 | date=26 October 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; Chelsea's streak of eleven consecutive away league wins, set between 5 April 2008 and 6 December 2008, is also a record for the English top flight.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/Magazinedettail/0,,12306~1491763,00.html |
 title=Chelsea in eleven heaven |
 publisher=FA Premier League |
accessdate = 18 January 2009|
date=8 December 2008 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Chelsea have recorded several &quot;firsts&quot; in English football. Along with Arsenal, they were the first club to play with shirt numbers on 25 August 1928 in their match against [[Swansea Town F.C.|Swansea Town]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamUnif/UnifNosNames.html |
 title=Shirt Numbers |
 work=England Football Online |
accessdate = 1 October 2006 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Chelsea were the first English side to travel by aeroplane to a domestic away match, when they visited [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 19 April 1957,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=96}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the first First Division side to play a match on a Sunday, when they faced [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 27 January 1974. On 26 December 1999, Chelsea became the first British side to field an entirely foreign starting line-up (no British or Irish players) in a Premier League match against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=27 December 1999 |
url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/premiership/chelsea/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/99/12/26/SOCCER_Southampton_Nightlead.html&amp;TEAMHD=chelsea&amp;DIV=prem&amp;TEAM=CHELSEA&amp;RH=Chelsea&amp;PREV_SEASON=1998 |
title=Southampton 1 Chelsea 2 |
work=Sporting Life |
accessdate=27 January 2007 |
author=Bradley, Mark}}&lt;/ref&gt; On 19 May 2007, they became the first team to win the FA Cup at the new [[Wembley Stadium]], having also been the last to win it at the old Wembley.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=20 May 2007 |
title=Something old, new and Blue|
url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0,,2083889,00.html |
work=The Observer |
accessdate=20 May 2007 |
author=Mitchell, Kevin}}&lt;/ref&gt;
After the conclusion of the 2007–08 season, Chelsea became the highest ranked club under [[UEFA coefficient|UEFA's five-year coefficient]] system used in the seeding of European club competitions in the following season, the first English club to do so in the 21st century.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.xs4all.nl/~kassiesa/bert/uefa/data/method3/trank2008.html |
 title=UEFA Team Ranking 2008 |
 work=UEFA European Cup Football: Results and Qualification |
 author=Kassies, Bert |
 accessdate = 2 June 2008 }}&lt;/ref&gt; On the final day of the 2009–10 season, Chelsea became the first team in Premier League history to score at least 100 goals in a single season.&lt;ref name=Wigan80/&gt;

==Popular culture==
[[File:Chelsea double winner 2009-10.JPG|thumb|250px|Chelsea parade through the streets of Fulham and Chelsea after winning their league and cup double, May 2010]]
In 1930, Chelsea featured in one of the earliest football films, ''[[The Great Game (1930 film)|The Great Game]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0020936/ |
 title=The Great Game |
 work=IMDb |
 accessdate = 1 October 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; One-time Chelsea centre forward, [[Jack Cock]], who by then was playing for [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], was the star of the film and several scenes were shot at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], including the pitch, the boardroom, and the [[dressing room]]s. It included guest appearances by then-Chelsea players [[Andrew Nesbit Wilson|Andrew Wilson]], [[George Mills (footballer)|George Mills]], and [[Sam Millington]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=120–121}}&lt;/ref&gt; Owing to the notoriety of the [[Chelsea Headhunters]], a [[football firm]] associated with the club, Chelsea have also featured in films about football [[hooliganism]], including 2004's ''[[The Football Factory (film)|The Football Factory]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=10 May 2004 |
url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/3687227.stm |
title=Football firms hit the film circuit |
publisher=BBC Sport |
accessdate=25 January 2007 |
author=Steve Hawkes}}&lt;/ref&gt; Chelsea also appear in the [[Hindi]] film ''[[Jhoom Barabar Jhoom]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=25 September 2006 |
url=http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?NewsID=1055099 |
title=Chelsea teams up with Yash Raj Films |
publisher=DNA India |
accessdate=1 January 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Up until the 1950s, the club had a long-running association with the [[music hall]]s, with their underachievement often providing material for comedians such as [[George Robey]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
date=30 September 2002 |
url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/Match_Report/0,1527,-39862,00.html |
title=Di Canio has last laugh at Chelsea comedy store |
work=The Guardian |
accessdate=1 January 2007 |
author=Scott Murray}}&lt;/ref&gt; It culminated in comedian Norman Long's release of a [[Novelty song|comic song]] in 1933, ironically titled &quot;On the Day That Chelsea Went and Won the Cup&quot;, the lyrics of which describe a series of bizarre and improbable occurrences on the hypothetical day when Chelsea finally won a trophy.&lt;ref name=&quot;glanville&quot;/&gt;

The song &quot;[[Blue is the Colour (Chelsea)|Blue is the Colour]]&quot; was released as a single in the build-up to the [[1972 Football League Cup Final|1972 League Cup Final]], with all members of Chelsea's first team squad singing; it reached number five in the [[UK Singles Chart]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=5791 |
 title=Blue Is The Colour |
 work=Chart Stats|
 accessdate = 21 January 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; (The song was later adopted, as an anthem, by the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (USL)|Vancouver Whitecaps]] in Canada, after being changed to &quot;White is the Colour&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.vancourier.com/issues02/045202/sports.html |
 archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080103163706/http://www.vancourier.com/issues02/045202/sports.html |
 archivedate=3 January 2008 |
 title=Caps' 'Proclaim' season opener |
 work=Vancouver Courier|
 accessdate = 21 January 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;) In the build-up to the [[FA Cup Final 1997|1997 FA Cup Final]], the song &quot;Blue Day&quot;, performed by [[Suggs (singer)|Suggs]] and members of the Chelsea squad, reached number 22 in the UK charts.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |
 url=http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=25206 |
 title=Blue Day |
 work=Chart Stats|
 accessdate = 21 January 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Bryan Adams]], a fan of Chelsea,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
 url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/chelsea/article2967989.ece |
 title=The soul of Chelsea in 50 moments|
 work=Times Online|
 date = 29 November 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; dedicated the song &quot;We're Gonna Win&quot; from the album ''[[18 Til I Die]]'' to the club.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |
 url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/1116450/Countdown-to-the-Champions-League-final-in-Moscow-Who-are-ya.html?offset=2 |
 title=Countdown to the Champions League Final in Moscow |
 work=The Sun|
 date = 2 May 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Chelsea Ladies==
{{details|Chelsea L.F.C.}}
Chelsea also operate a [[Women's association football|women's football]] team, [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]]. It has been affiliated to the men's team since 2004,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.femalesoccer.net/show_news_article.php?id=3523|title=Chelsea Moving On Up|publisher=FemaleSoccer.net|accessdate=2011-02-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; and is part of the club's Community Development programme. They play their home games at Imperial Fields, the home ground of [[Isthmian League Premier Division|Isthmian League]] club [[Tooting &amp; Mitcham United F.C.|Tooting &amp; Mitcham United]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LadiesNews/0,,10268~2117196,00.html | title=About the Ladies |work=chelseafc.com | accessdate=20 February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; The club won the Surrey County Cup in 2003, 2004, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009 and 2010,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.surreyfa.com/FixturesAndResults/previouswinners/Womens.htm|title=Womens Cup|publisher=surreyfa.com|accessdate=2011-02-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; and were promoted to the [[FA Women's Premier League National Division|Premier Division]] for the first time in 2005 as [[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division|Southern Division]] champions. In the [[2009–10 FA Women's Premier League|2009-10]] season, they finished 3rd in the Premier League, equalling their highest ever placing, and in 2010 were one of the eight founder members of the [[FA WSL|FA Women's Super League]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbusiness.co.uk/news/article/newsitem=195/title=eight+teams+successful+in+women%26%23039%3Bs+super+league+bid|title=Eight teams successful in Women's Super League bid|publisher=fcbusiness.co.uk|accessdate=2011-02-20 | location=London | first= | last= | date=2010-03-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[John Terry]], the current captain of the Chelsea men's team, is President of Chelsea LFC.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/oct/18/john-terry-chelsea-womens-football|title=John Terry digs deep to rescue Chelsea Ladies after funding cuts|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2011-02-20 | location=London | first=Tony | last=Leighton | date=2009-10-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

